ABC Workout App — Product Design Brief (V1.5)

Purpose
This app exists to make consistent, sustainable training easy to follow in real life. It should reduce thinking and friction, not increase them.

Core Product Philosophy
- Simplicity over maximum optimization
- Sustainability over perfect programming
- Consistency over idealized weekly structure
- Recommendations over enforcement
- Autoregulation over rigid rules
- Flexibility over guilt or reset behavior
- Something is better than nothing
- Manual override must always remain available

Training Philosophy
- The core system is a continuous A → B → C rotation
- The cycle should never reset based on calendar weeks
- Missed days are normal and should not break the system
- Double days are acceptable and should be handled gracefully
- RPE and subjective readiness are valid inputs
- Movement patterns matter more than chasing ideal volume targets
- The app may suggest balance and recovery adjustments, but should not become a compliance engine

What the App Should Do
- Remember context and recent history
- Recommend the next best workout based on existing context
- Surface soft advisories when useful
- Help compress training into real-life time constraints
- Preserve continuity across imperfect schedules
- Make logging and review easy
- Keep important data safe with export/import

What the App Should Not Do
- Enforce rigid scheduling
- Depend on weekly accounting
- Require perfect adherence
- Lock the user out of choices
- Push unnecessary complexity in pursuit of theoretical optimization
- Become a dashboard-heavy or quota-driven system
- Require a backend, account, or cloud dependency

Intelligence Rules
- Intelligence should be soft, trustworthy, and relatively rare
- Advisories should help, not nag
- Recommendations should be easy to override
- The app should not punish skipped days, unusual schedules, or manual choices
- Warnings should be calm and minimal
- If the app is already steering in the right direction, do not repeat yourself with extra advisories

Current Product Direction
- Base architecture is guided recommendation with manual override
- This is closer to “B with a light C layer underneath”
- The app can ask a few smart questions and adapt its recommendation
- The app should not become a rigid automated program controller

Architecture Principles
- Keep the app static and easy to maintain
- Prefer readable, low-risk code organization
- Keep logic easy to locate and understand
- Add features only when they clearly improve daily usability or system integrity
- Avoid abstractions that make the project harder for a non-expert owner to maintain

Feature Boundary
Good additions:
- readiness check
- post-session RPE
- fatigue advisories
- double-day carry advisories
- soft balance advisories
- export/import safety
- lightweight recommendation improvements

Bad additions:
- week-based enforcement
- volume quotas
- mandatory progression engines
- hard lockouts
- complex periodization systems
- backend/cloud complexity unless truly needed

Decision Standard
Before adding or changing anything, ask:
1. Does this reduce friction in real use?
2. Does this preserve simplicity and sustainability?
3. Does this make the app more helpful without making it more controlling?
4. Would I still want this if my schedule gets messy?
If not, do not add it.